Topic Classification

Overview¶

My work consist of both classification and clustering analysis.

Clustering:
I used two different approaches.

  • In the first one, I used Latent Dirichlet Allocation method and worked with the tf-idf scheme. I detected several (per-class) topics by considering the most powerful words.
  • In the second one, I constructed a Word Network upon which I applied Community Detection using the Louvain method. The detected communities express different topics. Also, I extracted features in order to improve my models performance regarding the classification task.


Classification:
I used two different representations, Td-idf and Word Embeddings.

  • In the first case I used several sklearn classifiers
  • In the second I implemented an LSTM in pytorch
    (In both cases I didn't tune the hyper-paremeters)

'''
arguments:
    doc: raw document as string
return:
    string containing the preprocessed words
'''

def my_preprocessor(doc):
    #convert the text to lower-case
    doc= doc.lower()
    #afairesi punctuation (may result in consecutive spaces)
    udoc = re.sub(r"[\W_]", ' ',doc)
    #convert consecutive spaces into one
    udoc = re.sub(r"\s+", ' ',udoc)
    #remove spaces from both the beginning and the end
    udoc= udoc.strip()
    return udoc


'''
arguments:
    doc: preprocessed document as string
return:
    list of tokens (strings)
'''

def my_tokenizer(doc):
    #tokenize
    words= doc.split()
    #remove stopwords
    filtered_words = [word for word in words if word not in STOP_WORDS]
    #remove article-specific stopwords
    filtered_words = [word for word in filtered_words if word not in my_stop_words ]
    #remove words with length == 1 (these words are: 'o','ή','α','β','γ','ε',','κ','ν','π','σ','χ','ό')
    filtered_words = [word.upper() for word in filtered_words if len(word) > 1]
    #stemming
    no_tone_words = []
    for word in filtered_words:
        no_tone_word = []
        for char in word:
            if char in tone_dict.keys():
                char = tone_dict[char]
            no_tone_word.extend(char)
        no_tone_word = ''.join(no_tone_word).upper()
        no_tone_words.append(no_tone_word)
    filtered_words = [stemmer.stem(word).lower() for word in no_tone_words]
    filtered_words = [word for word in filtered_words if len(word) > 1]
    return filtered_words

def no_stem_tokenizer(doc):
    #tokenize
    words= doc.split()
    #remove stopwords
    filtered_words = [word for word in words if word not in STOP_WORDS]
    #remove article-specific stopwords
    filtered_words = [word for word in filtered_words if word not in my_stop_words ]
    #remove words with length == 1 (these words are: 'o','ή','α','β','γ','ε',','κ','ν','π','σ','χ','ό')
    filtered_words = [word for word in filtered_words if len(word) > 1]
    return filtered_words

def PCA_plots(X_3d, labels, title='Kmeans'):
    #2D
    plt.figure()
    ax1 = plt.axes()
    for g in np.unique(labels):
        ix = np.where(labels == g)
        xs = X_3d[ix, 0]
        ys = X_3d[ix, 1]
        ax1.scatter(xs, ys, cmap="viridis", label=g+1 , s=9, alpha=0.7)
    ax1.set_xlabel('PC1')
    ax1.set_ylabel('PC2')
    ax1.legend(loc = 'upper left')
    plt.title(title + " - 2D projection")
    plt1 = plt
    # 3D
    plt.figure()
    ax = plt.axes(projection='3d')
    for g in np.unique(labels):
        ix = np.where(labels == g)
        xs = X_3d[ix, 0]
        ys = X_3d[ix, 1]
        zs = X_3d[ix, 2]
        ax.scatter(xs, ys, zs, cmap="viridis", label=g+1 , s=9, alpha=0.6)
    ax.set_xlabel('PC1')
    ax.set_ylabel('PC2')
    ax.set_zlabel('PC3')
    ax.legend(loc = 'lower left')
    plt.title(title + " - 3D projection")
    return plt1, plt

It becomes obvious that the two classes have many characteristics in terms of the vocabulary that is used and that is why Kmeans fails to separate them properly. More specifically, it seems that the language used by articles that belong to class 2 is a subset of that used by class 1. Therefore, we expect a larger variety of concepts and news pertaining to class 1 compared to class 2 which is expected to contain articles around limited concepts. Despite the low variance of the principal components these results are totally in agreement with those of the Latent Dirichlet allocation where we saw that class 2 was focused in greek poltics while class 1 contained random, "shocking" and low quality news from all over the world.

Conclusions:

  • All methods fail to seperate the interclass topics (mainly because classes are not exactly separated based on topic but by source)
  • During our research the three methods seemed to reach similar and consistent results in terms of class 1 as described in the previous section. (Shocking articles of drugs & war, top models etc. - Articles stemming mainly from click baiting news pages (e.g Newsbeast.gr))
  • However due to the fuzziness of class 2, different runs led to slightly different topics for class 2. (Internal & External politics of Greece, Breaking news, Sports Contracts - articles that come from serious news agencies of Greece (ΑΠΕ-ΜΠΕ))
  • The Kmeans algorithm seems to be more robust and seems to well separate terms inside intra class clusters.
  • In contrast to LDA, the k-means algorithm "hard" assigns our articles to their respective cluster while LDA assigns them to topics in a probabilistic way.

Community Detection | Louvain Method¶

In this section I will construct a Word Network, where:

  • edges: words
  • weights: #documents at which those 2 words are co-occuring

I will extract communities of words that the inter-connected weighted edges are much more dense that the cross-connected edges. This quantity is being called Modularity and the algorithm that maximizes it is called Louvain Method. This method runs in O(n^2) when n is the number of nodes.

In order to result in a small number of communities (topics), I had to prune the weak edges of the network and keep the size of the communities small in order them to pe interpretable. The first parameter is called support threshold, while the second resolution.

The rest of the analysis consist of 3 parts. In the first one I examined how the quantity we want to maximize relates to the support threshold and the resolution. After this parameter tuning, I run the Louvain Method and extracted the communities. Finally, I present the results.

b.2.1) Parameter Tuning¶

find the pairs count and store them in a NetworkX way

In [32]:
pairs_count= {}
label= 0
for doc in corpus[y==label]:
    #get all the tokens
    words= my_tokenizer(my_preprocessor(doc))
    
    #at least 2 tokens are needed to form a pair
    if len(words)<2:
        continue;
    
    #generate and count all possible pairs
    for i in range(len(words)):
        for j in range(i+1,len(words)):
            word1, word2= words[i], words[j]
            if word1 == word2 or word1==' ' or word2==' ':
                continue
            pair= tuple(sorted([word1,word2]))
            pairs_count[pair]= pairs_count.get(pair,0) + 1
            

#store them   
limit= 10 #remove the pairs (edges) having count less than 10

with open(pickles_path+'word_network_class_{}.weighted.edgelist'.format(label), 'w', encoding="utf-8") as f:
    for pair,count in pairs_count.items():
        if count > limit:
            f.write('{} {} {}\n'.format(pair[0],pair[1],count))

examine how Modularity relates to resolution and support threshold

In [33]:
def modularity_over_support(graph_file,res=1.0):
    
    def calculate_modularity():
        modularityList= []
        range_limit= range(10,100)
        nodes_num= []
        for limit in range_limit:
            ebig=[(u,v,d) for (u,v,d) in G.edges(data=True) if d['weight'] >= limit]
            G2=nx.Graph()
            G2.add_edges_from(ebig)
            nodes_num.append(len(G2.nodes()))
            comp= nx.connected_component_subgraphs(G2)
            big_cb= [ (cg,len(cg)) for cg in comp if len(cg)>=4]
            big_cb= sorted(big_cb, key= lambda t: t[1], reverse=True)
            partition = community.best_partition(big_cb[0][0],resolution=res)
            modularityList+= [community.modularity(partition,big_cb[0][0])]
        
        return range_limit, modularityList, nodes_num
    
    
    G= nx.read_weighted_edgelist(pickles_path+graph_file)
    range_limit, modularityList, nodes_num = calculate_modularity()
    return list(range_limit), modularityList, nodes_num

    G= nx.read_weighted_edgelist(pickles_path+graph_file)
    print(nx.info(G))
    print('\n_________________________\n\n')
    
    G= removeSmallEdges(suppor_limit, G)
    print('.... after pruning ....\n')
    print(nx.info(G))

    #keep the main connected component
    print('\n_________________________\n\n')
    print(nx.number_connected_components(G),' connected components')
    comp= nx.connected_component_subgraphs(G)
    big_cb= [ (cg,len(cg)) for cg in comp if len(cg)>=connCompSizeLimit]
    big_cb= sorted(big_cb, key= lambda t: t[1], reverse=True)
    print('\n',len(big_cb),' connected components with size >=',connCompSizeLimit)
    print(big_cb)
                  
    return G, big_cb


def removeSmallEdges(weight,G):
    ebig=[(u,v) for (u,v,d) in G.edges(data=True) if d['weight'] >= weight]
    return G.edge_subgraph(ebig)


def drawGraph(subG):
    plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
    pos = nx.spring_layout(subG)
    nx.draw_networkx_nodes(subG, pos, node_size = 10)
    nx.draw_networkx_labels(subG, pos, font_size= 15)
    nx.draw_networkx_edges(subG, pos)
    plt.show()

def community_detection(G,big_cb,res=1.0):
    
    def apriori(node):
        return sum([ edge[1]['weight'] for edge in G.adj[node].items()])

    def both(v1,v2):
        return G[v1][v2]['weight']

    def confidence(v1,v2):
        return both(v1,v2)/apriori(v1)

    def comb_confidence(v1,v2):
        return min(confidence(v1,v2),confidence(v2,v1))
    
    def best_partition():
        partition = community.best_partition(G,resolution=res)  
        print('\n_________________________\n\n')
        print(max(set(partition.values()))+1,' communities found')
        print('modularity is: ',community.modularity(partition,G))
        
        return partition
    
    
    def orginizeNodersPerCommunities(partition):
        communities= {}
        for num in set(partition.values()):
            communities[num]= []

        for node,com in partition.items():
            communities[com]= [node]+communities[com]
        
        lengthLouvainCom= len(communities)
        for num in range(lengthLouvainCom, lengthLouvainCom+len(rest_cb)):
            communities[num]= rest_cb[num-lengthLouvainCom][0].nodes()
            
        return communities
    
    
    def rankCommunities(communities):
        utilities= {}
        for com,nodeList in communities.items():
            utility = 0
            for pair in itertools.combinations(nodeList, 2): #once each pair!
                if pair[0] in G[pair[1]]:
                    utility+= comb_confidence(pair[0],pair[1])
            com_len= len(nodeList)
            utilities[com]= utility/(com_len+1)#(2*(len(nodeList)+1))
        
        return utilities
    
    
    def sortRankedCommunities(utilities, communities):
        sortedCommunities = [(k, utilities[k],len(communities[k])) for k in sorted(utilities, key=utilities.get, reverse=True)]
        print('\n_________________________\n\n')
        for communityInfo in sortedCommunities:
            print('community ',communityInfo[0],' has utility ',communityInfo[1],' and consist of ',communityInfo[2],' nodes')

        return sortedCommunities
            
    def findCommunities():
        partition= best_partition()
        communities= orginizeNodersPerCommunities(partition)
        utilities= rankCommunities(communities)
        sortedCommunities= sortRankedCommunities(utilities, communities)
        return communities, sortedCommunities
    
    main_cb= big_cb[0][0]
    rest_cb= big_cb[1:]
    communities, communitiesInfo= findCommunities()
    return communities, communitiesInfo

def get_additional_features(communities,word_to_com_map,com_size_dict,max_size):
    feats1= np.zeros((corpus.shape[0],len(communities.keys())))
    feats2= np.zeros((corpus.shape[0],len(communities.keys())))
    for i,doc in enumerate(corpus):

        #get all the tokens
        words= my_tokenizer(my_preprocessor(doc))

        #per community count
        com_occ= [word_to_com_map[word] for word in words if word in word_to_com_map]

        coms, cnts= np.unique(com_occ, return_counts=True)

        #feats - case 1: #words per community
        for c_i in range(len(coms)):
            feats1[i,coms[c_i]]= cnts[c_i]
            feats2[i,coms[c_i]]= cnts[c_i]/com_size_dict[coms[c_i]]
            
        return np.concatenate((feats1,feats2),axis=1)

Train/Test Split¶

Instead of sklearn train_test_split method, we implement our own one in order to have the exact same split in both the cases of the below classifiers (sklearn) and the LSTM (pytorch)</h4>

In [47]:
#force the random split to be the same over the model optimization process
def my_train_validation_split(X, y, ratio=[0.8,0.2], random_state=None):
    #np.random.seed(random_state)
    #indices of articles within each class
    y0_idx= np.hstack(np.argwhere(y==0))
    y1_idx= np.hstack(np.argwhere(y==1))

    #indices in-place shuffling
    np.random.shuffle(y0_idx)
    np.random.shuffle(y1_idx)

    #split
    dataset_size= X.shape[0]
    train_size= int(ratio[0]*dataset_size//2)
    
    train_idx= np.concatenate((y0_idx[:train_size], y1_idx[:train_size]))
    test_idx= np.concatenate((y0_idx[train_size:], y1_idx[train_size:]))
        
    return train_idx, test_idx

We split our data to train/ test sets for convenience purposes. The selected test set will never be used for model tuning and selection. It will be hidden from our models till the end of our demonstration in order to simulate real-life problems or competitions. For that reason, the initial traing set will be split to train and validation set for model selection purposes.

Bagging¶

In this section we seek to improve the performance of the tuned simple classifiers by applying the well known bootstrap aggregating method by using different number of bags in each iteration. We compare results to the previous ones of the tuned classifiers.

In [58]:
# =============================================================================
# 18b. Bagging Classifiers
# =============================================================================
print("Bagging Results (CV):\n")
for n in [10, 15,20]:
    print("Number of bags: {}".format(n))
    for model in models:
        bcl = BaggingClassifier(base_estimator = models[model] , n_jobs= -1, n_estimators = n)
        cv_score = np.mean(cross_val_score(bcl, X_train, y_train, cv=cv))
        print("{:.3f} [{}] -> Improvement: {:.3f} ".
              format(cv_score, model, cv_score - scores[model]))
    print("============================================")

Voting¶

The final step is to collect 3 of the best and most "dissonant" classifiers from above in terms of recall and combine them using a voting process so as to optimise our predictions. This means that we choose to combine 2 classifiers that tend to better predict class 0 with those that better predict class 1. The third classifier added to the scheme is chosen to be an "unbiased" (balanced) classifier in order to smoothen the conflicts between the two abovementioned classifiers.
So, we chose to keep LightGBM and combine AdaBoostSVM and k-NN which are quick and simple as the dissonant classifiers (kNN consistenly favoured class 0 in terms of recall). It may seem surprising but this simple set of models proved to be the most robust one during our different experiments and that's why we go on with this voting combination. Bagging classifiers were avoided for time efficiency purposes.

    y_train_we= [ y[i] for i in train_idx if i != 316]

    X_validation_we= [ corpus_we[i] for i in validation_idx  if i != 316]
    y_validation_we= [ y[i] for i in validation_idx if i != 316]

class FrameLevelDataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, feats, labels, max_seq_len, sort=False):
        """
            feats: Python list of numpy arrays that contain the sequence features.
                   Each element of this list is a numpy array of shape seq_length x feature_dimension
            labels: Python list that contains the label for each sequence (each label must be an integer)
        """
        
        self.lengths= torch.LongTensor(torch.from_numpy(  np.array([len(f) for f in feats])  ).long())
        
        mask = np.argsort(-self.lengths) if sort else np.arange(len(self.lengths))
        
        self.lengths= self.lengths[mask]
        self.feats= self.zero_pad_and_stack(feats, max_seq_len)[mask]
        self.labels= torch.LongTensor( np.array(labels).astype('int64') )[mask]
        self.len= self.feats.shape[0]

        
    def zero_pad_and_stack(self, X_list, max_seq_len):
        """
            This function performs zero padding on a list of features and forms them into a numpy 3D array
            returns
                padded: a 3D numpy array of shape num_sequences x max_sequence_length x feature_dimension
        """
        X_array_p = []
        for X in X_list:
            seq_len= X.shape[0]
            X_array_p.append(np.pad(X,[[0,max_seq_len-seq_len],[0,0]],mode='constant'))

        return torch.FloatTensor(torch.from_numpy(  np.array(X_array_p)  ).float())
    
    
    def __len__(self):
          return self.len
        
    def __getitem__(self,idx):
        return self.feats[idx], self.lengths[idx], self.labels[idx]

Create the LSTM¶

The following LSTM:

  • is bi-directional
  • has 2 fully-connected, linear layers above it
  • has features such as:
    • early stopping
    • regularization
    • dropout in the 2 linear layers
In [95]:
class BasicLSTM(nn.Module):
    
    
    def __init__(self, input_size, hidden_dim, output_size, n_layers, bidirectional=False, drop_prob=0, pack=False, printing=True):
        """ 
            x : 3D numpy array of dimension N x L x D
                N: batch index
                L: sequence index
                D: feature index

            lengths: N x 1
         """
        super(BasicLSTM, self).__init__()
        
        #features of our model
        self.bidirectional = bidirectional
        self.feature_size = (hidden_dim * 2) if self.bidirectional else hidden_dim
        self.num_directions = 2 if bidirectional else 1
        self.hidden_dim= hidden_dim
        self.output_size= output_size
        self.pack= pack
        self.my_print= print if printing else lambda *args: None
        
        #architecture
        self.lstm = nn.LSTM(input_size, self.feature_size, n_layers, bidirectional=self.bidirectional, dropout=drop_prob, batch_first=True)
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(drop_prob)
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(self.feature_size*self.num_directions, 64)
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(64, self.output_size)
        
        
    def forward(self, x, lengths):
        """ 
            x : 3D numpy array of dimension N x L x D
            N: batch index
            L: sequence index
            D: feature index
            lengths: N x 1
         """
        batch_size = x.size(0)
        self.my_print('input shape:',x.shape)
        if self.pack:
            x = nn.utils.rnn.pack_padded_sequence(x, lengths, batch_first=True)
            self.my_print('pack padded shape:',x.data.shape)
            lstm_out, _ = self.lstm(x.float())
            self.my_print('lstm out shape:',lstm_out.data.shape)
            lstm_out, _ = nn.utils.rnn.pad_packed_sequence(lstm_out,batch_first=True)
            self.my_print('pad packed shape:',lstm_out.shape)
        else:
            lstm_out, _= self.lstm(x)
            self.my_print('lstm out shape:',lstm_out.shape)
        
        out= self.last_timestep(lstm_out,lengths, bidirectional=self.bidirectional)
        self.my_print('last timestep shape:',out.shape)
        
        out = out.contiguous().view(batch_size, -1)
        self.my_print('last timestep converted:',out.shape)
        
        out = F.relu(self.fc1(out))
        out = F.log_softmax(self.fc2(self.dropout(out)), dim=1)
        self.my_print('dropout/fc1/fc2 out shape:',out.shape)
        self.my_print('softmax shape:',out.shape)
 
        return out
    

    def last_timestep(self, outputs, lengths, bidirectional=False):
        """
            Returns the last output of the LSTM taking into account the zero padding
        """
        if bidirectional:
            forward, backward = self.split_directions(outputs)
            last_forward = self.last_by_index(forward, lengths)
            last_backward = backward[:, 0, :]
            # Concatenate and return - maybe add more functionalities like average
            return torch.cat((last_forward, last_backward), dim=-1)

        else:
            return self.last_by_index(outputs, lengths)

    @staticmethod
    def split_directions(outputs):
        direction_size = int(outputs.size(-1) / 2)
        forward = outputs[:, :, :direction_size]
        backward = outputs[:, :, direction_size:]
        return forward, backward

    @staticmethod
    def last_by_index(outputs, lengths):
        # Index of the last output for each sequence.
        idx = (lengths - 1).view(-1, 1).expand(outputs.size(0),
                                               outputs.size(2)).unsqueeze(1)
        return outputs.gather(1, idx).squeeze()

def train_model(model, n_epochs, lr, criterion, optimizer, earlyStopping=None, checkpoints=None, checkValidationSet=False, pack=False):
    
    if earlyStopping:
        patience, min_delta, earlyStoppingBreak= earlyStopping['patience'], earlyStopping['min_delta'], earlyStopping['break'] 
        
    is_cuda = torch.cuda.is_available()

    if is_cuda:
        device = torch.device("cuda")
        print("GPU is available")
    else:
        device = torch.device("cpu")
        print("GPU not available, CPU used")

    model.to(device)

    train_losses= []
    val_losses= []
    alreadyStopped= False
    earlyStoppingEpoch= None
    smallest_val_error= np.inf

    # Training Run
    for epoch in range(1, n_epochs + 1):
        #training loss + weights update
        batch_loss = []
        for inputs, lengths, labels in (train_loader_p if pack else train_loader):
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            output = model(inputs, lengths)
            loss = criterion(output, labels)
            batch_loss.append(loss.item())
            loss.backward()
            optimizer.step()
        train_loss= np.mean(batch_loss)
        train_losses.append(train_loss)    
        
        
        #validation loss
        if earlyStopping or checkValidationSet:
            with torch.no_grad():
                batch_loss = []
                for inputs, lengths, labels in (validation_loader_p if pack else validation_loader):
                    output = model(inputs, lengths)
                    loss = criterion(output, labels)
                    batch_loss.append(loss.item())

            val_loss= np.mean(batch_loss)
            val_losses.append(val_loss)


        print('...... epoch: {}/{} ......\t'.format(epoch, n_epochs), end='')
        print('train loss {:.4f}'.format(train_loss), end='')
        if earlyStopping or checkValidationSet:
            print('    validation loss {:.4f}'.format(val_loss), end='')

        
        if checkpoints and not alreadyStopped and  val_losses[-1] < smallest_val_error:
            smallest_val_error= val_losses[-1]
            save_model(model,epoch,optimizer,train_loss,val_loss,filename=checkpoints['filename'])
            print('    saving model', end='')
            
        elif earlyStopping and not alreadyStopped and epoch>patience:
            last_scores= val_losses[-patience:]
            if last_scores[0] == min(last_scores) or abs(last_scores[0]-min(last_scores)) < min_delta:
                print('\nEarly Stopping at epoch',epoch)
                alreadyStopped= True
                earlyStoppingEpoch= epoch-patience
                if earlyStoppingBreak:
                    break
            
        print('')

    return train_losses, val_losses, earlyStoppingEpoch


def save_model(model,epoch,optimizer,train_loss,val_loss,filename='checkpoint.pt'):
    torch.save({
            'epoch': epoch,
            'model_state_dict': model.state_dict(),
            'optimizer_state_dict': optimizer.state_dict(),
            'train_loss': train_loss,
            'val_los': val_loss
            }, pickles_path+filename)

def print_loss_curve(train_losses,val_losses,earlyStoppingEpoch=None):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))
    if train_losses and val_losses:
        plt.plot(train_losses,label='train loss',color='b')
        plt.plot(val_losses,label='validation loss',color='g')
        if earlyStoppingEpoch:
            plt.axvline(earlyStoppingEpoch,linestyle='--',label='Early Stopping checkpoint',color='r')
        plt.legend()
        plt.title('Training/Validation Loss')
        plt.show()
    else:
        plt.plot(train_losses)
        plt.title('Training Loss')
        plt.show()

As you will see, the LSTM didn't perfom well enough in comparison with the rest classifiers. The 2 main reasons are:

  • The small size of the train set
  • The naive representation of the documents. As I already mentioned, I appended the word embeddings of all the words after preprocessing.

loaders= [train_loader_p, validation_loader_p, test_loader_p]
loadersNames= ['train set', 'validation set', 'test set']

for i,loader in enumerate(loaders):
    outputs, true_labels= [], []
    for inputs, lengths, labels in loader:
        output = model(inputs, lengths)
        outputs.append(np.argmax(output.detach().numpy(),axis=1))
        true_labels.append(labels.detach().numpy())
    
    outputs= [x for out in outputs for x in out] #restore the strange pytorch represantation
    true_labels= [x for lab in true_labels for x in lab]
    total= len(true_labels)
    TP= sum( np.equal(outputs, true_labels) )     
    print('Accuracy {:0.2f}% [{}]'.format(TP*100/total, loadersNames[i]))
